    <fr:title text="Non-empty sets and surjections › "><fr:link href="jms-00MA.xml" title="Non-empty sets and surjections" addr="jms-00MA" type="local">Non-empty sets and <fr:link href="jms-00M8.xml" title="Surjection" addr="jms-00M8" type="local">surjections</fr:link></fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is nonempty, so that we have some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>. We must show that for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in {\mathopen {}\left  [1\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, there exists some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[!_A{\mathopen {}\left (x\right )\mathclose {}}=i]]></fr:tex>. Letting <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i=0]]></fr:tex> be the unique element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left  [1\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we may set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x:= a]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 <fr:p>Conversely, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[!_A\colon  A\to {\mathopen {}\left  [1\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is surjective, we know that there exists some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[!_A=0]]></fr:tex>; therefore, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is nonempty.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
